  "prompt": "Japanese Etiquette, Behavior, and Habits: How does tipping work in Japan?",
  "response": "In Japan, tipping is not a common practice and is generally not expected. The Japanese culture places a strong emphasis on hospitality and high-quality service, which is considered a standard part of any transaction. Here are some key points to understand about tipping in Japan:\n\n1. **No Tipping Norm**: Unlike many Western countries, tipping is not customary in Japan. In fact, it can sometimes cause confusion or embarrassment. Service staff are compensated well and take pride in their work, so offering a tip can be seen as unnecessary or even insulting.\n\n2. **Exceptional Service**: If you feel compelled to show gratitude for exceptional service, it\u2019s better to express it verbally with a genuine thank you (\"arigatou gozaimasu\") or a small gift, rather than offering money.\n\n3. **Restaurants and Taxis**: In restaurants, the bill includes a service charge, so tipping is neither expected nor required. Similarly, taxi drivers do not expect tips, and rounding up the fare is not necessary.\n\n4. **Ryokans and Hotels**: In traditional inns (ryokans) or higher-end hotels, you might encounter a service charge included in your bill. If you wish to show appreciation to a particularly helpful staff member, a small gift or a thank-you note is more appropriate than cash.\n\n5. **Guides and Tour Operators**: For private guides or tour operators, tipping is not expected but can be appreciated if you feel they went above and beyond. If you decide to tip, present it discreetly in an envelope, as offering cash directly can be seen as impolite.\n\n6. **When in Doubt, Avoid Tipping**: If you\u2019re unsure, it\u2019s better to err on the side of not tipping. Japanese people are generally more comfortable with verbal gratitude or a polite bow.\n\nRespecting local customs and norms is an essential part of visiting or interacting with any culture. In Japan, understanding the etiquette around tipping can help you navigate social situations more smoothly and show respect for the local way of life.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
